{
  format: 1
  name: combinators-lack-precedence-and-grouping-unspecified
  suite: static
  tags: [grammar, combinators, precedence, adversarial]
  // Pedantic-implementer probe: chain three view combinators of different kinds
  // where the grouping changes the result. '.a | .b & .c' evaluates to
  // '(.a | .b) & .c' or '.a | (.b & .c)' with different membership. Annex C.8
  // and §7.4 list each binary combinator (| & - ?? and the ?: form) but state
  // NO precedence, NO associativity, and provide NO grouping-parenthesis syntax
  // at all. So neither the meaning of this expression nor whether it is even
  // well-formed (absent any way to disambiguate) is deducible.
  note: "Annex C.8 / §7.4 enumerate the view combinators but define neither relative precedence nor associativity, and the grammar exposes no grouping-parenthesis form to disambiguate a mixed chain such as '.a | .b & .c'. Whether such an expression is well-formed, and if so how it groups, is not deducible from SPEC.md."
  spec: ["#annex-c", "§C.8", "#views", "§7.4"]

  package: {
    $liasse: 1
    $app: "t.combprec@1.0.0"
    $model: {
      items: {
        $key: "id"
        id: "text"
        a: "bool"
        b: "bool"
        c: "bool"
      }
      mixed: {
        $view: ".items[:i | i.a] { id } | .items[:i | i.b] { id } & .items[:i | i.c] { id }"
      }
      $public: {
        items: { $view: ".mixed" }
      }
    }
  }

  expect: {
    outcome: unspecified
  }
}
